dot2desc is a tool that, given a valid dot file representing possible executions of a litmus test as produced by herd, will describe those executions in English in a Markdown file.
The tool actually produces Markdown with inlined LaTeX, which requires post-processing with pandoc using the catdefinitions.tex file inside the herdtools repository.
Below is a step-by-step guide on how one can use dot2desc on a specific litmus test.

1. Ensure the tool is built and installed in our path
    # Checking out the branch will not be necessary once the pull request is merged
    git checkout dot2desc
    make && make install

2. Run herd on the litmus test to build the dot file (skip this test if you already have a dot file)
    # The -show all -showevents all configuration will work fine in most cases and will produce the most informative dot file
    # Feel free to explore with other configurations
    ~/bin/herd7 -show all -showevents all test_name.litmus -o .

    This will have produced a file called test_name.dot in the current directory.
    If we want to produce the file in a different directory, it can be specified with the -o option, as above.

3. Run dot2desc
    Note: This will alter the dot file by eliminating some unnecessary information, so that the graph
    becomes more minimal and suitable for inclusion in the Arm ARM.

    ~/bin/dot2desc7 test_name.dot > example.md

    Now we have a Markdown file that could look something like this (example was generated using an LDR instruction on a memory location tagged with green):

    -   D~1~: \iicodata{\RREof{X0}}{\ImpTagMREof{\taglocOf{x}{\memlocAddrBy{x}{X0}}}}.

    -   D~2~: \iicodata{\RREof{X0}}{\IntrBranching{\iseqCheck{\allocTagOf{x}}{\logAddrTagIn{X0}}}}.

    -   D~3~: \iicodata{\ImpTagMREof{\taglocOf{x}{\memlocAddrBy{x}{X0}}}}{\IntrBranching{\iseqCheck{\allocTagOf{x}}{\logAddrTagIn{X0}}}}.

    -   D~4~: \iicodata{\RREof{X0}}{\ExpMREof{\memlocAddrBy{x}{X0}}}.

    -   C~1~: \iicoctrl{\IntrBranching{\iseqCheck{\allocTagOf{x}}{\logAddrTagIn{X0}}}}{\ExpMREof{\memlocAddrBy{x}{X0}}}.

    -   D~5~: \iicodata{\ExpMREof{\memlocAddrBy{x}{X0}}}{\RWEof{X1}}.

4. Expand the inlined LaTeX.
    All the LaTeX commands we can see above should be defined (and their definitions can be changed) in the catdefinitions.tex file.
    If any of them is missing, that command will not be expanded at the end of this step.
    The contents of the fix-formatting.lua and capitalize.lua scripts are given in the appendix.

    # This produces a big LaTeX file with the contents of example.md and catdefinitions.tex embedded.
    # It assumes the command is run from the root of the herdtools7 repository.
    # If the current directory is different, the correct path to catdefinitions.tex should be given.
    pandoc -f markdown+raw_tex+latex_macros+subscript --wrap=preserve --preserve-tabs --lua-filter=fix-formatting.lua example.md -o out.tex -H herd/libdir/catdefinitions.tex

    # Some LaTeX syntax post-processing...
    sed -i '' 's/#1#2/[2]/g' out.tex

    # Replaces the LaTeX commands with their contents
    pandoc out.tex --wrap=preserve --lua-filter=capitalize.lua -o res.md


After step 4, we should have a complete description of all valid executions of some_test.litmus described inside red.md.

Appendix:

fix-formatting.lua:
function RawInline(el)
  if el.format == "tex" then
    local updated_text = el.text
      :gsub("~([^~]+)~", "\\textsubscript{%1}") -- Fix subscripts
      :gsub("`([^`]+)`", "\\texttt{%1}")       -- Fix monospace
    return pandoc.RawInline("tex", updated_text)
  end
end

capitalize.lua:
function capitalize_first_word(inlines)
    local found_colon = false  -- Track when we encounter ':'

    for i, elem in ipairs(inlines) do
        if elem.t == "Str" then
            -- Check if this element contains only ":"
            if elem.text:match(":$") then
                found_colon = true  -- Found the colon, next word should be capitalized
            elseif found_colon then
                -- Capitalize the first lowercase letter after the colon
                inlines[i] = pandoc.Str(elem.text:gsub("^(%l)", string.upper, 1))
                break  -- Only modify the first word after ':'
            end
        end
    end

    return inlines
end

function BulletList(el)
    -- Process each list item inside the unordered list
    for _, item in ipairs(el.content) do
        for _, block in ipairs(item) do
            if block.t == "Plain" or block.t == "Para" then
                block.content = capitalize_first_word(block.content)
            end
        end
    end
    return el
end